Ideally no light would be directly transmitted from the illuminator to the camera. Is this the case?

At JH request, on 24 Aug 2015 AT collected camera frames reresenting:

  • white reference sample, illuminator on,
  • dark reference sample, illuminator on,
  • dark reference sample, illuminator off.

Turned out dat files were corrupt due to pointer shenanigans.

RD repeated data collection process 2 Sept 2015. He noted that it was "bloody hard to line up to the dark slot". I had imagined the lining up process as an essential set up step and a precursor to testing the backscatter. Obviously this is a poor assumption. That the camera and slit are not optimally aligned makes what follows susceptible to small changes in alignment.

What does the data look like?¶

Lets start by taking a look at the data RD collected Sept 2, 2015:

Populating the interactive namespace from numpy and matplotlib

Some observations:

  • large number of bad pixels. More than on the last camera? MR dosn't think so, but is going to check with the manufacturer.
  • lots of saturated pixels in white reference image!
  • repeatability looks good. I'll quantify how good below.
  • white reference images indicate 5 or 10% more illumination at the ends of the illumintor compared to the middle. Probably due to reflections from end walls. Perhaps these should have been painted black? They will mess with the incident light directional distribution as well.
  • why (for the most part) is there a lower limit to reflectance?

How repeatable are pixel values?¶

In [96]:
pylab.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (15, 5)
# frames 1--20 are of white ref, lamps on
def plot_range(frames, lbl):
    W = numpy.dstack(frames).astype(float)
    W[W==0]=1
    subplot(121)
    pcolor((W.max(axis=2)-W.min(axis=2))/4095.*100)
    axis((1,320,1,256))
    colorbar()
    title('%s : range as %% of full scale' % lbl)
    subplot(122)
    pcolor((W.max(axis=2)-W.min(axis=2))/W.mean(axis=2)*100)
    axis((1,320,1,256))
    colorbar()
    title('%s : range as %% of average' % lbl)
    show()
plot_range(R[0:20], 'white/on')
# frames 21--30 are of dark ref, lamps on
plot_range(R[20:30], 'dark/on')
# frames 31--40 are of dark ref, lamps off
plot_range(R[30:40], 'dark/off')

Repeatability is very good. Typically less than 1% f.s.

The region of very low variability in the white ref imagery is probably a consequence od saturation.

I wonder what causes the stripy artefacts? Maybe the sensor is composite silicon???

Removing high variance pixels cleans things up a bit, but doesn't get rid of all the spikes. Presumably these are pixels having substantially different characteristics compared to their neighbours, but otherwise stable.

Backscattered light¶

Assuming the dark reference reflects no light, backscattered light (light reaching the camera directly from the illuminator) is the difference between what the camera sees when targeting the dark reference with and without the illuminator lamps on.

In [101]:
# backscattered light % relative to full scale
W = ma.masked_where(V>range_crit, dstack(R[0:20]).mean(axis=2))
D = ma.masked_where(V>range_crit, dstack(R[20:30]).mean(axis=2))
DD = ma.masked_where(V>range_crit, dstack(R[30:40]).mean(axis=2))
pcolor((D-DD)/4095.*100)
axis((1,320,1,256))
colorbar();
In [102]:
# backscattered light % relative to white ref
M = (D-DD)/W*100
pcolor(M)
print(M.mean(), M.std())
axis((1,320,1,256))
colorbar();

(2.7688038478760126, 0.62644375595673751)

Looks like, in absolute terms, more light is backscattered from the illuminator ends than along the length, but relative to the white reference the amount of backscattered light is small ~2+/-0.6% but possibly not negligible.

Spectrally the backscattered light is similar to that relfected from the white reference. This will NOT be true of light reflected from wood and will introduce error in chemometric predictions from edge pixels.

Conclusions¶

  • A repeatable procedure for optimally aligning the camera and illuminator slit is required.

  • The camera has ~300 noisy pixels (~0.3%) whose values should be ignored. Is this similar to previous camera?

  • Bad pixel positions should be written into every data file, but should bad pixels be identified as part of

    • a setup/calibration process?
    • at the time of each scan? (by collecting and analysisng multiple white/dark frames)

  • The current camera settings are collecting too much light leading to pixel saturation. Either turn down the lamp brightness or reduce the integration (exposure) time. There needs to be reasonable saftey margin since wood samples have been observed to reflect more than the white reference on occasion. Perhaps target a raw maximum white reference reflectance of 3700?

  • Some light from the illuminator is being directly observed by the camera. The illuminator end walls are the primary source of this light.

  • Try making the illuminator end walls non-reflective (paint them black, or maybe temporarily insert black paper/cloth?) then repeat this analysis. Alternatively don't use pixels near the edges for mapping samples perhaps by masking off the illuminator slot?
